&gt;On 7/12/05, Andrew McDonagh &lt;andrew.mcdonagh@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;Instead of code using Java&#39;s System.currentTimeInMillis() method
&gt;&gt;directly, they get the time via an abstract factory. The production code
&gt;&gt;concrete factory does the usual System.currentTimeInMillis() whereas the
&gt;&gt;tests use a Test Concrete Factory that is preconfigured to always return
&gt;&gt;the same value.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;public interface SystemTimeFactory {
&gt;&gt;   long currentTimeInMillis();
&gt;&gt;   long currentTimeInSeconds();
&gt;&gt;}
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Yes, we seem to have found the same general approach. 
&gt;

Cool!

&gt;But I think this
&gt;can be improved as more than a simple facade - most code that wants to
&gt;get time has a higher level idea that just looking at raw time. So you
&gt;can use instead something like:
&gt;
&gt;public interface Timer {
&gt;    void start();
&gt;    void stop();
&gt;    void reset();
&gt;    long secondsElapsed();
&gt;}
&gt;
&gt;The implementation, both for production and test are obvious and
&gt;simple, and the additional level of indirection is easily justified by
&gt;the abstraction.
&gt;
&gt;
